There is a write-up in Robert Charles Anderson's series, The Great Migration, for Kathern and her husband Robert.  This series is considered to be the "gold standard" in the area of early New England settlers and was written by Robert Charles Anderson, who is considererd to be the world expert on early New England settlers.  See source below.  We see on page 101 that Kathern, age 28, was registered with her husband in 1634 to come to Massachusetts on the ship Elizabeth.  They brought with them three children - Mary, Abraham, and Isaacke. 

Kathern doesn't appear by name in any records (except the ship log), but it appears that she had several more children while living in Salem, including Elizabeth, Sarah, Zachariah, Jacob, and Hannah.  Her husband remarried in 1669, so she must have died before this time.  

Robert and Kathern had eight known children, including the 3 born in England:
*1. Mary b. about 1630;
2. Abraham b. about 1632;
3. Isaac b. about 1633 (their ages given on the ship passenger list);
4. Elizabeth b. about 1636 (estimate based on marriage before 1658);
5. Sarah b. about 1638;
6. Zachariah baptized 1640;
7. Jacob baptized 1640/1; and
8. Hannah baptized 1645.

On page 107 we find the following:  "In her will of 1 March 160[1/]2, "Elizabeth Goodale" of Dennington, Suffolk, mentioned three sons, incuding Robert and "Henry Kilham and Alice his wife, my daughter"...this latter couple were the parents of Austin Killam...and this may be what led George E. Williams to claim that the first wife of Robert Goodale was "Catherine Kilham."  While there is no evidence for this identification, the fact that one of the daughters of Robert Goodale married a son of Austin Killham suggest that there may be some relationship."  
Robert Charles Anderson does not appear to be impressed with the work of George E. William, which he says, especially regarding the early years of the settler Robert Goodale, relies "overmuch on tradition and speculation."
